 -- DistroForge maintainers <maintainers@distroforge.invalid>  Sun, 31 May 2026 22:49:35 +0200

distroforge (0.3.0-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Add ForgeAdvisor, an advisory-only build assistant that perceives, explains
    and proposes but never mutates the build, recipe or ISO on its own: every
    change still crosses the same explicit-action wall (a GUI Apply or a CLI
    verb the user runs) as the rest of the product. It works in four rings —
    silent perception, free explanation, previewable proposals, and execution
    only via that wall — and is governed by the four founding pillars rather
    than added as a fifth. New CLI verbs (forgeadvisor explain-log /
    review-build / propose-fixes / doctor-ai) each mirror a GUI surface on the
    Maintainer page, keeping CLI/GUI parity.
  * Ground the advisor in a host-owned build-memory corpus that records every
    build attempt — success or failure — with its options, signatures and log
    features, so guidance cites real history ("3 of your last 5 builds failed
    at squashfs") rather than hallucinating. A pluggable, local-first reasoning
    backend degrades to a fully offline grounded-heuristic mode: with no backend
    it still perceives, classifies and cites the corpus, never blocking and
    never requiring the network. No model weights ship in the core package.
  * Unify failure diagnosis on one canonical taxonomy (core/build_diagnosis.py):
    the beginner-iso --explain-last-failure explainer and ForgeAdvisor both
    delegate to it, so a failure class means exactly one thing wherever it is
    shown or counted.
  * Reframe the GUI around a journey spine: a workflow-level gate persisted
    across sessions, a spine home, reframed step panels, a goal hub and a
    command palette that exposes every action, favouring recognition over
    recall without renaming or removing any capability.
  * Add two further contract documents — UX cognitive-ergonomics and
    velocity/responsiveness — and back the advisory agent with an inviolable
    governance contract; each is phrase-locked and verified by tests so the
    behaviour cannot silently drift.

